  volume    =  158,
  number    =  23,
  abstract  = "Second-order Møller-Plesset perturbation theory (MP2) often
               breaks down catastrophically in small-gap systems, leaving much
               to be desired in its performance for myriad chemical applications
               such as noncovalent interactions, thermochemistry, and dative
               bonding in transition metal complexes. This divergence problem
               has reignited interest in Brillouin-Wigner perturbation theory
               (BWPT), which is regular at all orders but lacks size consistency
               and extensivity, severely limiting its application to chemistry.
               In this work, we propose an alternative partitioning of the
               Hamiltonian that leads to a regular BWPT perturbation series
               that, through the second order, is size-extensive,
               size-consistent (provided its Hartree-Fock reference is also),
               and orbital invariant. Our second-order size-consistent
               Brillouin-Wigner (BW-s2) approach can describe the exact
               dissociation limit of H2 in a minimal basis set, regardless of
               the spin polarization of the reference orbitals. More broadly, we
               find that BW-s2 offers improvements relative to MP2 for covalent
               bond breaking, noncovalent interaction energies, and
               metal/organic reaction energies, although rivaling
               coupled-cluster with single and double substitutions for
               thermochemical properties.",
  month     =  jun,
  year      =  2023,
  language  = "en"
}

